"Abstract With the proliferation of online activities, the computer has become the target of criminal conduct, if not the vehicle for the commission of offences. What is commonly known as hacking is a crime unique to computers. So is modification of computer data, introduction of worms and bombs, and not least, the disruption of computer service. Computer intrusion might be perpetrated by an outsider, hacking from one computer to another or by an insider. The position is clear-cut in respect of the outside hacker. Less straightforward, at least until recently, is the case of internal misuse: where computer access is authorized but put to an unauthorized use. It is the latter position with which this article is primarily concerned."
